;; ch08-inventory-and-world-state.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 8: Inventory and World-State

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      8
  :title               "Inventory and World-State"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"An adventure game is a state machine. The player is in a room. The
door is locked. The player picks up a key. The state changes. Now the
door is unlocked, or at least can be. Everything the player does is a
state transition; every scene reads the state to decide what to
render.

Inventory is a subset of world-state — specifically the items the
player is carrying. World-state is the bigger set: what's true about
the world right now. Is the well poisoned? Has the sister come home?
Did the villain die in scene 12? All of that is world-state.

Cortex is our state store. Inventory is one Cortex key holding a list.
World-state is many Cortex keys holding flags. Simple. What's hard is
the discipline of writing scenes that always read state before
rendering, and always update state after significant actions.

---

## 8.1 Inventory as a list

```scheme
;; Add an item to inventory.
(define (pick-up item)
  (let ((inv (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())))
    (cortex/write 'inventory (cons item inv))
    (paint-text 20 400
      (string-append \"You picked up \" (item->prose item) \".\"))))

;; Drop an item.
(define (drop item)
  (let ((inv (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())))
    (cortex/write 'inventory (filter (lambda (i) (not (eq? i item))) inv))
    (paint-text 20 400
      (string-append \"You dropped \" (item->prose item) \".\"))))

;; Check if you have something.
(define (have? item)
  (member item (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())))

;; Item to prose (English article + name).
(define (item->prose item)
  (case item
    ((lantern) \"the lantern\")
    ((key)     \"a small brass key\")
    ((rope)    \"a coil of rope\")
    ((letter)  \"a folded letter\")
    ((feather) \"a white feather\")
    (else      (string-append \"a \" (symbol->string item)))))
```

Four verbs — pick up, drop, have?, item->prose — and you have a
working inventory. Every scene can consult `(have? 'lantern)` before
deciding whether to offer the enter-the-cave option.

The `filter` in `drop` returns a new list with all elements except the
dropped one. This is standard list-processing. If you have multiple
copies of the same item and only want to drop one, use a more careful
`remove-first` — but for narrative games, one copy of each item is
usually plenty.

Notice we do NOT delete an item when it is used. We might read
'you have the lantern' in scene 8 and light the darkness. In scene 15
we still have the lantern. Real inventory only drops when the player
explicitly drops it OR when a scene explicitly consumes it (like
handing over the letter).

---

## 8.2 Consuming items

Sometimes handing over an item removes it from inventory.

```scheme
;; Give an item to someone.
(define (give item npc)
  (drop item)
  (cortex/write (npc-received-key npc item) #t)
  (paint-text 20 400
    (string-append (npc-name npc) \" takes \" (item->prose item)
                   \" from your hand.\")))

(define (npc-received-key npc item)
  (string->symbol
    (string-append \"gift/\" (symbol->string npc)
                   \"/\" (symbol->string item))))

;; Later, Mira can react:
(define (mira-check-gift)
  (cond
    ((cortex/read 'gift/mira/letter)
     \"MIRA: 'The letter — you brought it? Thank you.'\")
    ((cortex/read 'gift/mira/feather)
     \"MIRA: 'The feather. From the hawk on the ridge?'\")
    (else
     \"MIRA: 'You have empty hands. That is fine too.'\")))
```

`give` drops the item from your inventory AND records a Cortex flag
saying you gave THIS item to THIS npc. That flag survives forever.
Ten scenes later, another NPC can say 'Mira told me about the
letter.' The economy of the world tracks itself.

The compound key trick — `gift/mira/letter` — lets you have any
number of gift-relationships without a giant hardcoded flag list.
Every gift is its own flag. Reading them later is a matter of building
the key.

---

## 8.3 World-state flags

Beyond inventory, the world has state that is not carried by anyone.

```scheme
;; Common world-state keys.
;;
;;   'state/door-unlocked?
;;   'state/well-poisoned?
;;   'state/village-burned?
;;   'state/sister-home?
;;   'state/villain-killed?
;;
;; Read them:
(if (cortex/read 'state/sister-home?)
    (paint-text 20 40 \"Your sister is in the kitchen, humming.\")
    (paint-text 20 40 \"The kitchen is empty. She is not back yet.\"))

;; Write them:
(cortex/write 'state/sister-home? #t)
```

Prefer `?`-suffixed boolean keys. They read naturally in code:
`(if (cortex/read 'state/sister-home?) ...)` reads like English.

Prefer flat namespaces. `state/well-poisoned?` is better than
`village/well/water/poisoned?`. Deep hierarchies feel organized but
make the code longer. The narrative game usually has 30-100 flags —
that fits in a flat namespace fine.

---

## 8.4 The inventory bar

Players want to see what they are carrying. Paint a bar at the bottom
of the screen showing current inventory.

```scheme
;; Paint an inventory bar along the bottom.
(define (paint-inventory-bar)
  (let ((inv (or (cortex/read 'inventory) '())))
    (paint-text 20 550 \"CARRYING:\")
    (let loop ((items inv) (i 0))
      (when (not (null? items))
        (paint-text (+ 110 (* i 80)) 550
          (item-icon-or-name (car items)))
        (loop (cdr items) (+ i 1))))))

(define (item-icon-or-name item)
  (case item
    ((lantern) \"[lantern]\")
    ((key)     \"[key]\")
    ((rope)    \"[rope]\")
    ((letter)  \"[letter]\")
    (else      (string-append \"[\" (symbol->string item) \"]\"))))
```

Call `paint-inventory-bar` at the end of every scene's render pass.
The player sees, at all times, what they are carrying. This is a
small courtesy that saves hours of frustration — 'do I have the key?
Where does it show up?'

For a fancier bar, replace the bracketed text with sprite icons via
`entity/sprite!` on a dedicated inventory-bar entity per item. But
text works fine; do not over-engineer.

---

## 8.5 Gating scenes on state

A scene checks state before rendering. If the state does not allow
the scene, redirect or offer a partial version.

```scheme
(define (enter-the-cave)
  (cond
    ((have? 'lantern)
     (scene-cave-lit))
    (else
     (scene/imagine)
     (surface/paper)
     (paint-text 20 40 \"The cave is pitch dark. You cannot see three\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"feet in front of you.\")
     (paint-text 20 100 \"You back out. You would need a light.\")
     (world/after 90 (lambda () (previous-scene))))))
```

The player can enter the cave with a lantern (full scene) or without
(short warning-and-back). Never let the player walk into a state the
game cannot handle — always give a graceful bounce back.

For multi-item gates:

```scheme
(define (enter-the-tower)
  (cond
    ((and (have? 'key) (have? 'letter))
     (scene-tower-full))
    ((have? 'key)
     (scene-tower-locked-inside))
    (else
     (scene-tower-locked-outside))))
```

Three different scenes based on inventory. Each is fully written; each
reads differently for the player who arrives in that state.

---

## 8.6 A worked scene: five rooms, seven items

Here is a small puzzle-adventure. Five rooms. Seven items to find.
One exit. The player must assemble a specific combination to leave.

```scheme
;; The five rooms.
(define (kitchen)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"KITCHEN. A pot on the stove. A window over a garden.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (if (have? 'pot) \"\" \"[A] take the pot\"))
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[B] to the garden   [C] to the hall\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (unless (have? 'pot) (pick-up 'pot)) (kitchen))
        ((b) (garden))
        ((c) (hall))))))

(define (garden)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"GARDEN. Tomatoes. A well. A shed.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (if (have? 'tomato) \"\" \"[A] pick a tomato\"))
  (paint-text 20 130 (if (have? 'water)  \"\" \"[B] fill a container from the well\"))
  (paint-text 20 160 \"[C] enter the shed   [D] back to kitchen\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (unless (have? 'tomato) (pick-up 'tomato)) (garden))
        ((b) (if (have? 'pot)
                 (begin (pick-up 'water) (garden))
                 (begin (paint-text 20 220
                          \"You have no container.\") (garden))))
        ((c) (shed))
        ((d) (kitchen))))))

(define (shed)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"SHED. A hoe. A coil of rope. Dust.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (if (have? 'hoe)  \"\" \"[A] take the hoe\"))
  (paint-text 20 130 (if (have? 'rope) \"\" \"[B] take the rope\"))
  (paint-text 20 160 \"[C] back to garden\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (unless (have? 'hoe) (pick-up 'hoe)) (shed))
        ((b) (unless (have? 'rope) (pick-up 'rope)) (shed))
        ((c) (garden))))))

(define (hall)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"HALL. Stairs up. A door out (locked).\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (if (have? 'lantern) \"\" \"[A] take the lantern from the hook\"))
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[B] upstairs   [C] to kitchen\")
  (paint-text 20 160
    (if (and (have? 'key) (have? 'lantern) (have? 'rope))
        \"[D] open the door and leave\"
        \"\"))
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (unless (have? 'lantern) (pick-up 'lantern)) (hall))
        ((b) (upstairs))
        ((c) (kitchen))
        ((d) (when (and (have? 'key) (have? 'lantern) (have? 'rope))
               (leave)))))))

(define (upstairs)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"UPSTAIRS. A bedroom. A key on the dresser.\")
  (paint-text 20 100 (if (have? 'key) \"\" \"[A] take the key\"))
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[B] back down\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (unless (have? 'key) (pick-up 'key)) (upstairs))
        ((b) (hall))))))

(define (leave)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"You unlock the door. Rope tied to the doorframe,\")
  (paint-text 20 70 \"lantern in one hand, key in the other. You step\")
  (paint-text 20 100 \"out into the yard. You made it.\"))
```

Five rooms, seven items (pot, tomato, water, hoe, rope, lantern, key),
one exit. The exit needs key + lantern + rope. Water is a red herring
— it makes the world feel real without being required. Tomato is
another red herring — some players will try to bring it, and nothing
bad will happen either way.

Red herrings are important. If every item is required, the puzzle is a
fetch quest. If some items are optional, the player has to think about
which are which. Better yet, some optional items unlock BONUS scenes
— take the tomato home, hand it to the neighbor, get a small
sub-story.

---

## 8.7 The chair — an example of world-state that isn't inventory

There is a chair in the corner. If you sit in it, you fall asleep and
dream of your sister. But you can only sit in it once. This is
world-state, not inventory.

```scheme
(define (the-chair)
  (cond
    ((cortex/read 'state/slept-in-chair?)
     (paint-text 20 200 \"The chair is empty. You have already slept.\"))
    (else
     (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] sit in the chair\")
     (on-key
       (lambda (k)
         (when (eq? k 'a)
           (cortex/write 'state/slept-in-chair? #t)
           (dream-of-sister)))))))
```

The `state/slept-in-chair?` flag survives forever. The player who
comes back tomorrow cannot sit in the chair a second time. The
one-shot dream becomes a one-shot memory.

This is important design: some scenes should not repeat. Dreams,
confessions, deaths, farewells. Gate them with a `state/*` flag and
respect it forever.

---

## 8.8 Common desktop tasks — an operator's virtual bookshelf

An operator sells vintage books. She wants a page where the customer
can 'browse a bookshelf' — pick up a book, read its jacket, put it
back or add to cart. State-tracked so returning customers see which
books they have already read summaries of.

```scheme
(define-card 'browse-bookshelf
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)
    (paint-text 20 40 \"A shelf of six books. Which one interests you?\")

    (let* ((books '(the-riverside-cook the-copper-tea rustic-tables
                    a-year-in-glass the-quiet-hours night-thoughts))
           (read-titles (or (cortex/read 'browse/read-jackets) '())))
      (let loop ((bs books) (i 0))
        (when (not (null? bs))
          (paint-text 20 (+ 100 (* i 30))
            (string-append \"[\" (number->letter (+ i 1)) \"] \"
                           (book->title (car bs))
                           (if (member (car bs) read-titles)
                               \"  (jacket read)\"
                               \"\")))
          (loop (cdr bs) (+ i 1))))

      (on-key
        (lambda (k)
          (let ((idx (letter->index k)))
            (when (and (>= idx 0) (< idx 6))
              (let ((chosen (list-ref books idx)))
                (cortex/write 'browse/read-jackets
                  (cons chosen (or (cortex/read 'browse/read-jackets) '())))
                (show-jacket chosen)))))))))
```

Six books. The customer picks one. The card records that she read
that jacket. Next time she comes, that book is marked (jacket read).
She can browse jackets she hasn't seen. When she is ready to buy, a
sub-scene lets her add to cart.

The operator did what a bookseller does: made a shelf, let the
customer touch things. State keeps track so the customer doesn't feel
like she is starting from zero on each visit.

---

## 8.9 Routing patterns

**Consumable vs persistent items.** Some items — letters, gifts —
are consumed on use. Others — lanterns, keys — persist. Decide up
front for each item; do not surprise the player mid-game.

**One-shot vs repeatable scenes.** Some scenes happen once ever. Some
repeat. Mark one-shots with `state/*-done?` flags and check them at
scene entry. If a player has already seen the dream, do not offer it
again.

**Explicit vs implicit gates.** Explicit gate: 'you need the key to
open this door — you can see the lock.' Implicit gate: 'the door
looks weird, you cannot figure out how to open it.' Explicit is
kinder for kids. Implicit is more rewarding for puzzle-focused
players. Choose based on your audience.

---

## 8.10 Closing

You have inventory. You have world-state flags. You can gate scenes on
state. You have written a five-room puzzle that a friend could play
in ten minutes.

The state store is the skeleton of your game. Every scene reads it;
every action writes to it. Get this discipline right and everything
downstream — dialogue, camera, sound — has a solid foundation.

Chapter 9 is the sound layer. A soundscape can carry state as well:
music changes as the player approaches the villain, silence lands
when a beat needs weight.")
